## Fix: database_project/database_branch silently stripped by SDK serialization

### Context
The synced table was still created in the production branch despite the previous fix.
Root cause: `_build_synced_table_payload` used the SDK path (`SyncedDatabaseTable` object)
when `databricks-sdk` is installed (which is always the case in the deployed app).
`SyncedDatabaseTable` does not have `database_project` or `database_branch` fields, so:
1. Passing them raised `TypeError` → the catch fell back to `database_instance_name` only.
2. Even without TypeError, `_to_dict` calls `obj.as_dict()` which silently drops unknown fields.

The dict path does not have this problem — `_to_dict(dict)` returns the dict unchanged,
preserving all fields including `database_project` and `database_branch`.

### Change

1. **`src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/SyncedTableManager.py`**
   - `_build_synced_table_payload`: always returns a plain dict (via `_build_synced_table_dict`)
     instead of conditionally returning an SDK object.  The SDK object path is removed entirely
     for payload construction.  The `_build_synced_table_sdk` method is retained but no longer
     called from `_build_synced_table_payload`.

### Modified files
- `src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/SyncedTableManager.py`

### Test result
31/31 passed

